Part 1 - Exploratory Analysis of Loan Data from Prosper¶

by Tumininu Adesimbo Sosanya¶

Introduction¶

This Loan Data Set from Prosper contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income, and many others.

What is the struture of your dataset?¶

There are 113,937 loans in the dataset with total number of missing values to be 136,4086.

This dataset contains 81 features of these loans (loan amount, borrower rate, current loan status, borrower income and many more).

Most varibales are numeric in nature, but we have 'IncomeVerifiable', 'CurrentlyInGroup', 'IsBorrowerHomeowner' which are boolean(also qualitative), and 17 objects (also qualitative).

ProsperRiskScore variable is ordinal as it is an ordered factor variable with following levels: Worse (Highest Risk) ----> Best(Lowest Risk)

The LoanStatus is a categorical variable with distinct levels: Charged off, Current, Cancelled, PastDue, Completed, FinalPaymentsInProgress.

What are the main features of interest in your dataset?¶

I am most interested in figuring out what features are best in predicting the borrower rate of a loan and features that affect loan status.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

There are so many features that can support my investigation but I would focus more on 'ProsperRiskScore', 'BorrowersEmploymentStatus' and 'StatedIncomeLevel' as I am of the opinion that these factors can influence the 'BorrowersRate' and also be a stong determinant for the 'LoanStatus'

We will do some more cleaning here.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformation?¶

I performed a log transform on the variable 'StatedMonthlyIncome,' and discovered that it is close to normal, with a peak between 8 and 10 log-scaled monthly income.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

I noticed that the 'ProsperScore' has a lot of missing entries, which is due to the fact that it is only collected for loans beginning in 2015 and above, so I dropped all data collected prior to 2015.

Bivariate Exploration¶

To start off with, I want to look at the pairwise correlations present among features in the data.

           cmap = 'vlag_r', center = 0)

The above data show a weak negative correlation between monthly income and borrower rate, aswell as, a weak positive correlation between monthly income and Prosper Score. However, we can see a strong negative correlation between Borrower Rate and Prosper Score.
